Answers to questions

1.What years are included in this data set? What are the dimensions of the data frame and what are the variable or column names? the years 1940-2002 are included in this data sets. The dimensions of the data frame are [1] 63 3 and the variable names are boys, girls, and year.

  1. How do these counts compare to Arbuthnots? Are they on a similar scale? These counts while not similar in terms of number count are very similar in terms of proportion and ratio of sex at birth. The scale of arbuthnots counts are in the thousands, while the present counts differ as they are in the magnitude of millions.

3.Make a plot that displays the boy-to-girl ratio for every year in the data set. What do you see? Does Arbuthnots observation about boys being born in greater proportion than girls hold up in the U.S.? Include the plot in your response.

plot(present$year, ratio, type = "l") #plots the ratio of gender at birth

Within the above plot, I see that the ratio, while having a slight declining trend over time, is always above 1, which means that boys in the years are always being born in greater proportion than girls, much like arbuthnots observations centuries ago.

  1. In what year did we see the most total number of births in the U.S.? You can refer to the help files or the R reference card http://cran.r-project.org/doc/contrib/Short-refcard.pdf to find helpful commands.
max(present$boys + present$girls) #finds the max value of the total number of births in the U.S.
## [1] 4268326

4,268,326 total births is the most births seen in the U.S. from the years 1940-2002.
